Continuing birds first located by Jesse Pope a few days ago.  I first spotted one bird perched next to its nest on the transformer station.  A few minutes later the other bird flew in and perched next to the first.  Later, they flew behind the transformer station (as seen from Sweetwater Branch road) and found an apple tree with some still hanging fruit.  I observed them eat that fruit, and so it seems they have some source of food beyond the local feeders.  Later, I observed one of the two snap off a twig and then take it to the nest, indicating, as Jesse noted, that they are actively building the nest.  Please see the attached pictures which show the two birds near their nest, one feeding on an apple, and one flying with a twig in its beak.

Observation Details: Construyendo dos nidos en sendos eucaliptos. El 23 de septiembre R. Montesinos compartió el avistamiento con nosotros y otros compañeros. Él observó 4 cotorras alimentándose de higos y mencionó que volaban entre estos árboles frutales y unos eucaliptos. Hoy que tuvimos oportunidad de visitar el lugar y confirmamos la construcción de dos nidos en los que trabajaban arduamente (tres cotorras en cada nido). Se observaron alimentándose de hojas de eucalipto y acarreando ramas del mismo árbol para la construcción de su nido. Mientras estuvimos observándolas en ningún momento vimos que las cotorras se alimentaran de las hojas donde estaban construyendo los nidos; por el contrario, se iban hacia otro eucalipto y ahí eran donde cortaban ramitas de hojas para alimentarse.

Media notes: Monk Parakeet
Observation Details: Almost immediately Keith, Poppa, and I saw 2 of the 5 recently reported Monk Parakeets.  They were by their large nest in the center median of the turn-in, in the westernmost of 5 palm trees.  These palms are immediately W of the Gilbert Town Square entry sign. The parakeets stayed only a handful of minutes, then flew due S between the street and the nearby Pei Wei.  I walked around the outside of the connected buildings checking distant palms but saw no Monks.  However, at 7:45a.m. the two birds flew back to the nest.  Busily, they worked on the structure and were still there when we left.  ///  To best see the action, stand in the NE corner of Pei Wei parking (in the decorative gravel by the stucco stub wall).  Look up at the fifth palm and the nest fills the base of the palm fronds.

Continuing birds first located by Jesse Pope a few days ago.  I first spotted one bird perched next to its nest on the transformer station.  A few minutes later the other bird flew in and perched next to the first.  Later, they flew behind the transformer station (as seen from Sweetwater Branch road) and found an apple tree with some still hanging fruit.  I observed them eat that fruit, and so it seems they have some source of food beyond the local feeders.  Later, I observed one of the two snap off a twig and then take it to the nest, indicating, as Jesse noted, that they are actively building the nest.  Please see the attached pictures which show the two birds near their nest, one feeding on an apple, and one flying with a twig in its beak.

Previously reported; a lifer for me! Found the massive stick nest atop the utility pole first, then waited over an hour for the bird to arrive. Eventually it flew into the nest at about 7:30, and about twenty minutes later it came almost fully out, sitting on the edge to scratch its head and watch the sunset. Retreated back into the nest at about 8 PM, presumably for the night. Shockingly green on the back and wings, with a grey forehead, cheeks, chest, and stomach. Pale peachy-orange bill. Perhaps about the size of a dove, maybe a little smaller.

Media notes: Monk Parakeet
Observation Details: Almost immediately Keith, Poppa, and I saw 2 of the 5 recently reported Monk Parakeets.  They were by their large nest in the center median of the turn-in, in the westernmost of 5 palm trees.  These palms are immediately W of the Gilbert Town Square entry sign. The parakeets stayed only a handful of minutes, then flew due S between the street and the nearby Pei Wei.  I walked around the outside of the connected buildings checking distant palms but saw no Monks.  However, at 7:45a.m. the two birds flew back to the nest.  Busily, they worked on the structure and were still there when we left.  ///  To best see the action, stand in the NE corner of Pei Wei parking (in the decorative gravel by the stucco stub wall).  Look up at the fifth palm and the nest fills the base of the palm fronds.

Media notes: One member of a flock of at least 16 resident Monk Parakeets photographed by Curtis A. Marantz on 31 January 2022 at Rockwood Park in Calexico, Imperial County, california.
Observation Details: Dean began hearing the parakeets within a minute or two of our arrival, and shortly thereafter, we saw a flock of about 16 birds fly by us thought the middle of the park.  We ten observed a flock of at least 16 birds perched on wires and utility poles in the southeastern corner of the park before a few birds flew off.  Over the remainder of our visit, we saw scattered birds at various locations around the park and in the nearby neighborhood, but we never saw more than 16 individuals.  Alerting us to these birds were their screeching calls that sounded deeper than those of a Brotogeris, yet they sounded more like these birds than like the deeper calls of at least the Red-crowned Psittacara parakeets.  While under observation, these birds typically perched on utility wires or poles, but we did see a few parakeets perched in trees.  They were also quiet and relatively sedate when perched, calling primarily when they took flight or were in flight.  A few of these birds appeared to be paired and perched together and preening each other, but most were perched far enough apart along the wires to suggest that they were single. These were medium-sized parakeets that I estimated to be comparable in length to the Psittacara parakeets, yet they seemed a bit plumper overall and possibly to have larger heads and stockier necks.  The bill was deep-based and with a strongly decurved culmen that ended at a hooked tip, but I never clearly saw the lower mandible, which appeared to be hidden by the facial feathering.  I further thought the bill would have extended no farther back on the face than the rear part of the eye even though the vertical length from the base of the upper mandible to the culmen was longer than would it appear in horizontal distance.  The forehead was steep and the crown was gently rounded to somewhat flattened, but the junction of the forehead and crown was more strongly rounded than the junction of the crown with the nape, which was more gently and smoothly rounded, all on a head that was large in proportion to the size of the birds.  The neck was short and stout, and the body was relatively plump, full-cheated, and having a posture that was at least as upright as diagonal, if not even more upright, and with the long tail held downward in the plane of the body.  The wings were quite long, with the narrowly tapered wingtips reaching right about to the tips of the outermost rectrices, which themselves reached just beyond the midway point on the tail.  I further noted that the primary projection exceeded the entire length of the exposed secondaries, albeit not by too much, but I was unable to determine the number of primary tips visible beyond the longest secondary.  The tail was relatively long, in that it was about as long as the head, neck, and body combined, and it tapered to a narrowly pointed tip, but also with the underside of the tail showing a strong graduation of the various rectrices beginning with the outermost pair, which as noted above fell at or just beyond the midway point of the tail.  The medium-length undertail-coverts tapered to a pointed tip that I think reached about a third of the way out the tail, but this is not now clear in my memory.  The legs were not seen well, in large part because they appeared to be quite short, but the toes were stout and also relatively short. These were colorful and well-marked birds.  The forehead was light gray from the base of the upper mandible up to its junction with the crown roughly above the eye, and with the line of demarcation sharp and extending upward from the eye to the center of the forecrown.  Behind the gray forehead, the crown, nape, back, and scapulars were the typical, bright lime-green of a parakeet and lacking any internal markings.  This same green color extended down across the upper part of the head to the eye and back through the supraloral region and the back and sides of the neck.  As I recall, the demarcation between green and gray on the face extended back from the eye along the upper edge of the auriculars to their rear terminus before curving around along the side of the neck to the shoulder.  The throat and underparts in general were about the same shade of light gray as the forehead, if not even lighter on the lower part of the face and the auriculars, but on the breast and sides there was a pattern of indistinct and somewhat blurry barring.  The belly and flanks contrasted as a bit more yellowish than the breast and sides, in that we noted no yellow tones whatsoever on the gray of the breast and sides, yet on the belly and flanks the grayish color had a distinct yellowish cast.  The thighs were lime-green and the undertail coverts were yellowish-green from roughly the vent region to the tips of the longest feathers, but I am unsure to what degree the greenish color extending onto the lower part of the belly.  The underside of the tail was a more bronzy-yellow, and as I recall, lacking obvious, green tones.  Contrasting sharply with the gray underparts, the wings were mostly the same lime-green color as the upperparts, and with the upperwing coverts lacking any obvious contrast.  I am less sure about the color if the primary coverts, however.  The tertials were the same green as the coverts, and I suspect the secondaries were as well, though my recollection of this is not as good.  I did note quite clearly in the field that the exposed primaries were a sky-blue color that contrasted conspicuously with the mostly green wings, but I was unsure if the inner webs of the primaries were similarly colored.  I am confident that the upperside of the tail was green, but I am less sure if it was the same shade as the wings, or possibly a bit darker. The bill was a deep flesh color, and the toes were gray with a pinkish cast when seen in good light.  My photos show the eyes to be quite dark and that they were encircled by a light gray orbital-ring, neither of which I could recall from my field observations.

Media notes: Two members of a flock of at least 16 resident Monk Parakeets photographed by Curtis A. Marantz on 31 January 2022 at Rockwood Park in Calexico, Imperial County, California.
Observation Details: Dean began hearing the parakeets within a minute or two of our arrival, and shortly thereafter, we saw a flock of about 16 birds fly by us thought the middle of the park.  We ten observed a flock of at least 16 birds perched on wires and utility poles in the southeastern corner of the park before a few birds flew off.  Over the remainder of our visit, we saw scattered birds at various locations around the park and in the nearby neighborhood, but we never saw more than 16 individuals.  Alerting us to these birds were their screeching calls that sounded deeper than those of a Brotogeris, yet they sounded more like these birds than like the deeper calls of at least the Red-crowned Psittacara parakeets.  While under observation, these birds typically perched on utility wires or poles, but we did see a few parakeets perched in trees.  They were also quiet and relatively sedate when perched, calling primarily when they took flight or were in flight.  A few of these birds appeared to be paired and perched together and preening each other, but most were perched far enough apart along the wires to suggest that they were single. These were medium-sized parakeets that I estimated to be comparable in length to the Psittacara parakeets, yet they seemed a bit plumper overall and possibly to have larger heads and stockier necks.  The bill was deep-based and with a strongly decurved culmen that ended at a hooked tip, but I never clearly saw the lower mandible, which appeared to be hidden by the facial feathering.  I further thought the bill would have extended no farther back on the face than the rear part of the eye even though the vertical length from the base of the upper mandible to the culmen was longer than would it appear in horizontal distance.  The forehead was steep and the crown was gently rounded to somewhat flattened, but the junction of the forehead and crown was more strongly rounded than the junction of the crown with the nape, which was more gently and smoothly rounded, all on a head that was large in proportion to the size of the birds.  The neck was short and stout, and the body was relatively plump, full-cheated, and having a posture that was at least as upright as diagonal, if not even more upright, and with the long tail held downward in the plane of the body.  The wings were quite long, with the narrowly tapered wingtips reaching right about to the tips of the outermost rectrices, which themselves reached just beyond the midway point on the tail.  I further noted that the primary projection exceeded the entire length of the exposed secondaries, albeit not by too much, but I was unable to determine the number of primary tips visible beyond the longest secondary.  The tail was relatively long, in that it was about as long as the head, neck, and body combined, and it tapered to a narrowly pointed tip, but also with the underside of the tail showing a strong graduation of the various rectrices beginning with the outermost pair, which as noted above fell at or just beyond the midway point of the tail.  The medium-length undertail-coverts tapered to a pointed tip that I think reached about a third of the way out the tail, but this is not now clear in my memory.  The legs were not seen well, in large part because they appeared to be quite short, but the toes were stout and also relatively short. These were colorful and well-marked birds.  The forehead was light gray from the base of the upper mandible up to its junction with the crown roughly above the eye, and with the line of demarcation sharp and extending upward from the eye to the center of the forecrown.  Behind the gray forehead, the crown, nape, back, and scapulars were the typical, bright lime-green of a parakeet and lacking any internal markings.  This same green color extended down across the upper part of the head to the eye and back through the supraloral region and the back and sides of the neck.  As I recall, the demarcation between green and gray on the face extended back from the eye along the upper edge of the auriculars to their rear terminus before curving around along the side of the neck to the shoulder.  The throat and underparts in general were about the same shade of light gray as the forehead, if not even lighter on the lower part of the face and the auriculars, but on the breast and sides there was a pattern of indistinct and somewhat blurry barring.  The belly and flanks contrasted as a bit more yellowish than the breast and sides, in that we noted no yellow tones whatsoever on the gray of the breast and sides, yet on the belly and flanks the grayish color had a distinct yellowish cast.  The thighs were lime-green and the undertail coverts were yellowish-green from roughly the vent region to the tips of the longest feathers, but I am unsure to what degree the greenish color extending onto the lower part of the belly.  The underside of the tail was a more bronzy-yellow, and as I recall, lacking obvious, green tones.  Contrasting sharply with the gray underparts, the wings were mostly the same lime-green color as the upperparts, and with the upperwing coverts lacking any obvious contrast.  I am less sure about the color if the primary coverts, however.  The tertials were the same green as the coverts, and I suspect the secondaries were as well, though my recollection of this is not as good.  I did note quite clearly in the field that the exposed primaries were a sky-blue color that contrasted conspicuously with the mostly green wings, but I was unsure if the inner webs of the primaries were similarly colored.  I am confident that the upperside of the tail was green, but I am less sure if it was the same shade as the wings, or possibly a bit darker. The bill was a deep flesh color, and the toes were gray with a pinkish cast when seen in good light.  My photos show the eyes to be quite dark and that they were encircled by a light gray orbital-ring, neither of which I could recall from my field observations.

Media notes: Monk Parakeet
Observation Details: Almost immediately Keith, Poppa, and I saw 2 of the 5 recently reported Monk Parakeets.  They were by their large nest in the center median of the turn-in, in the westernmost of 5 palm trees.  These palms are immediately W of the Gilbert Town Square entry sign. The parakeets stayed only a handful of minutes, then flew due S between the street and the nearby Pei Wei.  I walked around the outside of the connected buildings checking distant palms but saw no Monks.  However, at 7:45a.m. the two birds flew back to the nest.  Busily, they worked on the structure and were still there when we left.  ///  To best see the action, stand in the NE corner of Pei Wei parking (in the decorative gravel by the stucco stub wall).  Look up at the fifth palm and the nest fills the base of the palm fronds.

Walking north on 31st Av S, I heard a loud screech in a tree in boulevard on east side of the road. I stopped and looked but couldn’t locate bird, though it had sounded as if it were right above me. Then it flew past, a lime green streak. It perched on a high branch of a tree in a yard a few doors south on 31st. I had my binoculars with me and quickly saw it was a parrot — or, as I learned later, a parakeet. I immediately took it for an escaped pet. Generally green, with a gray forehead (so to speak), lower face, throat, & breast. My partner took a few pictures (attached), and we pointed it out to the family in whose yard the bird was now perched. We watched it for five minutes, then left.

Media notes: Monk Parakeet
Observation Details: Almost immediately Keith, Poppa, and I saw 2 of the 5 recently reported Monk Parakeets.  They were by their large nest in the center median of the turn-in, in the westernmost of 5 palm trees.  These palms are immediately W of the Gilbert Town Square entry sign. The parakeets stayed only a handful of minutes, then flew due S between the street and the nearby Pei Wei.  I walked around the outside of the connected buildings checking distant palms but saw no Monks.  However, at 7:45a.m. the two birds flew back to the nest.  Busily, they worked on the structure and were still there when we left.  ///  To best see the action, stand in the NE corner of Pei Wei parking (in the decorative gravel by the stucco stub wall).  Look up at the fifth palm and the nest fills the base of the palm fronds.

Flock of 5 birds observed in the parking lot of the Pei Wei / Chipotle restaurants.  Observed in the palm trees in the median of the main Center access road  next to the stop light, then in a tree in the parking lot of the Phoenecia restaurant to the south.  They flew together to the west and I was unable to refind them.

Media notes: Monk Parakeet
Observation Details: Almost immediately Keith, Poppa, and I saw 2 of the 5 recently reported Monk Parakeets.  They were by their large nest in the center median of the turn-in, in the westernmost of 5 palm trees.  These palms are immediately W of the Gilbert Town Square entry sign. The parakeets stayed only a handful of minutes, then flew due S between the street and the nearby Pei Wei.  I walked around the outside of the connected buildings checking distant palms but saw no Monks.  However, at 7:45a.m. the two birds flew back to the nest.  Busily, they worked on the structure and were still there when we left.  ///  To best see the action, stand in the NE corner of Pei Wei parking (in the decorative gravel by the stucco stub wall).  Look up at the fifth palm and the nest fills the base of the palm fronds.

Three birds landed near nest; two returned with sticks and perched in tree near nest; one deposited stick in nest.  Birds we saw were located in grass alley just beyond 508 Hubbard in Yacolt.  Were told by lifetime resident that birds have been there since 2003 and at the peak there were 15 nesting pairs.  He also said they like to nest under transformers on power poles because the transformers generate warmth and protect the birds from the 88 inches of annual rain.  Utility workers destroy these nests as they can cause power failures when nests cause transformers to overheat.  Residents seem to enjoy the unique birds and will let you know where they have seen them recently. Some homeowners have also built nesting platforms in their yards such as the one pictured below.

This large flock of birds was very busy building a new "apartment complex" today.  Fun to watch.

I visited this sight on April 11, 2014 and photographed what was then a thriving community of parakeets with at least 30 birds busily building their nest.  Today their communal effort was largely in disrepair, since the hawks had taken up residence on the roof.  There were still at least three parakeets in the area.  They would perch on the same utility towers, high above the female hawk, but never did get too close to the nest.  It was a very odd interaction between two magnificent species of bird.

Observation Details: Pics; most likely an escaped bird;  I am extremely interested in this species and have been keeping an eye on their populations around Arizona and the US. I have tracked these birds ever since I had heard they once nested in Casa Grande.  I even interviewed several of the neighbors around the monk colony in that neighborhood. In 2012, I heard several calling parakeets in Casa Grande but have not been able to relocate them since that time.  Every year, I have gone back to Casa Grande to check certain spots.    Phoenix, Tempe and several other spots have seen these birds over the past two years.  If they are breeding, I don't know where they are doing it. Most are not I suspect, but there is one colony that will continue to be monitored. I know full well that they are capable of building some larger nests. California has a strong dislike for them:) As long as they have water nearby, telephone poles, pine or palm trees, they'll do it.  So far this year, from the people who have seen this parakeet(also known in the Pet Trade as a Quaker), there has not been any evidence.   My follow ups from my interviews with several of the Casa Grande neighbors indicated that they were very loud and annoying.  Since they are considered an invasive species in many states, including Arizona, a company may have been hired to "get rid" of the birds.  One of the neighbors alluded to the fact that someone had come out at one point and then they were gone.  I have always wondered if several escaped and went elsewhere.   So more thoughts to ponder about the Monk Parakeets in the Phoenix area.  Are some survivors from that Casa Grande nest?  How many if not all of them were intentionally or accidentally released into the wild by owners who didn't want the birds anymore?  And are they breeding?  For ABA listers or beginning birders, the Monk Parakeet is not "countable" here in Phoenix. However, it is a species of interest to me and several other people. We've put a lot of time and effort into these birds over the past years. Some might say "wasting" time:) Sometimes it's not about listing or finding "legit" birds.  Sometimes it's about observation and interaction studies. Today we had some fun observing the bird interact with the RFLO.  Rosy-faced Lovebirds(also once not ABA countable) have expanded and continue growing in numbers around the Phoenix area.  This year I saw several wild Lovebirds in the Tucson area. Is their population growing? How did they get there? More escaped birds?  Monk Parakeets were once countable in Casa Grande. If they were left alone, could their population numbers grow as well?  These were just some observations and interactions that I am finally able to write into a log since we tracked down this reported Monk Parakeet.  Most likely an escapee since it is alone.  But there are others that are in smaller colonies.  Keeping track of birds like the Nanday Parakeets, Monk Parakeets and Rosy-faced Lovebirds here in AZ is also an important piece to the larger puzzle about understanding our ever changing birdscape in AZ and the US.

One member of a flock of at least 16 resident Monk Parakeets photographed by Curtis A. Marantz on 31 January 2022 at Rockwood Park in Calexico, Imperial County, california.
Observation Details: Dean began hearing the parakeets within a minute or two of our arrival, and shortly thereafter, we saw a flock of about 16 birds fly by us thought the middle of the park.  We ten observed a flock of at least 16 birds perched on wires and utility poles in the southeastern corner of the park before a few birds flew off.  Over the remainder of our visit, we saw scattered birds at various locations around the park and in the nearby neighborhood, but we never saw more than 16 individuals.  Alerting us to these birds were their screeching calls that sounded deeper than those of a Brotogeris, yet they sounded more like these birds than like the deeper calls of at least the Red-crowned Psittacara parakeets.  While under observation, these birds typically perched on utility wires or poles, but we did see a few parakeets perched in trees.  They were also quiet and relatively sedate when perched, calling primarily when they took flight or were in flight.  A few of these birds appeared to be paired and perched together and preening each other, but most were perched far enough apart along the wires to suggest that they were single. These were medium-sized parakeets that I estimated to be comparable in length to the Psittacara parakeets, yet they seemed a bit plumper overall and possibly to have larger heads and stockier necks.  The bill was deep-based and with a strongly decurved culmen that ended at a hooked tip, but I never clearly saw the lower mandible, which appeared to be hidden by the facial feathering.  I further thought the bill would have extended no farther back on the face than the rear part of the eye even though the vertical length from the base of the upper mandible to the culmen was longer than would it appear in horizontal distance.  The forehead was steep and the crown was gently rounded to somewhat flattened, but the junction of the forehead and crown was more strongly rounded than the junction of the crown with the nape, which was more gently and smoothly rounded, all on a head that was large in proportion to the size of the birds.  The neck was short and stout, and the body was relatively plump, full-cheated, and having a posture that was at least as upright as diagonal, if not even more upright, and with the long tail held downward in the plane of the body.  The wings were quite long, with the narrowly tapered wingtips reaching right about to the tips of the outermost rectrices, which themselves reached just beyond the midway point on the tail.  I further noted that the primary projection exceeded the entire length of the exposed secondaries, albeit not by too much, but I was unable to determine the number of primary tips visible beyond the longest secondary.  The tail was relatively long, in that it was about as long as the head, neck, and body combined, and it tapered to a narrowly pointed tip, but also with the underside of the tail showing a strong graduation of the various rectrices beginning with the outermost pair, which as noted above fell at or just beyond the midway point of the tail.  The medium-length undertail-coverts tapered to a pointed tip that I think reached about a third of the way out the tail, but this is not now clear in my memory.  The legs were not seen well, in large part because they appeared to be quite short, but the toes were stout and also relatively short. These were colorful and well-marked birds.  The forehead was light gray from the base of the upper mandible up to its junction with the crown roughly above the eye, and with the line of demarcation sharp and extending upward from the eye to the center of the forecrown.  Behind the gray forehead, the crown, nape, back, and scapulars were the typical, bright lime-green of a parakeet and lacking any internal markings.  This same green color extended down across the upper part of the head to the eye and back through the supraloral region and the back and sides of the neck.  As I recall, the demarcation between green and gray on the face extended back from the eye along the upper edge of the auriculars to their rear terminus before curving around along the side of the neck to the shoulder.  The throat and underparts in general were about the same shade of light gray as the forehead, if not even lighter on the lower part of the face and the auriculars, but on the breast and sides there was a pattern of indistinct and somewhat blurry barring.  The belly and flanks contrasted as a bit more yellowish than the breast and sides, in that we noted no yellow tones whatsoever on the gray of the breast and sides, yet on the belly and flanks the grayish color had a distinct yellowish cast.  The thighs were lime-green and the undertail coverts were yellowish-green from roughly the vent region to the tips of the longest feathers, but I am unsure to what degree the greenish color extending onto the lower part of the belly.  The underside of the tail was a more bronzy-yellow, and as I recall, lacking obvious, green tones.  Contrasting sharply with the gray underparts, the wings were mostly the same lime-green color as the upperparts, and with the upperwing coverts lacking any obvious contrast.  I am less sure about the color if the primary coverts, however.  The tertials were the same green as the coverts, and I suspect the secondaries were as well, though my recollection of this is not as good.  I did note quite clearly in the field that the exposed primaries were a sky-blue color that contrasted conspicuously with the mostly green wings, but I was unsure if the inner webs of the primaries were similarly colored.  I am confident that the upperside of the tail was green, but I am less sure if it was the same shade as the wings, or possibly a bit darker. The bill was a deep flesh color, and the toes were gray with a pinkish cast when seen in good light.  My photos show the eyes to be quite dark and that they were encircled by a light gray orbital-ring, neither of which I could recall from my field observations.

The forehead was light gray from the base of the upper mandible up to its junction with the crown roughly above the eye, and with the line of demarcation sharp and extending upward from the eye to the center of the forecrown.  Behind the gray forehead, the crown, nape, back, and scapulars were the typical, bright lime-green of a parakeet and lacking any internal markings.  This same green color extended down across the upper part of the head to the eye and back through the supraloral region and the back and sides of the neck.  As I recall, the demarcation between green and gray on the face extended back from the eye along the upper edge of the auriculars to their rear terminus before curving around along the side of the neck to the shoulder.  The throat and underparts in general were about the same shade of light gray as the forehead, if not even lighter on the lower part of the face and the auriculars, but on the breast and sides there was a pattern of indistinct and somewhat blurry barring.  The belly and flanks contrasted as a bit more yellowish than the breast and sides, in that we noted no yellow tones whatsoever on the gray of the breast and sides, yet on the belly and flanks the grayish color had a distinct yellowish cast.  The thighs were lime-green and the undertail coverts were yellowish-green from roughly the vent region to the tips of the longest feathers, but I am unsure to what degree the greenish color extending onto the lower part of the belly.  The underside of the tail was a more bronzy-yellow, and as I recall, lacking obvious, green tones.  Contrasting sharply with the gray underparts, the wings were mostly the same lime-green color as the upperparts, and with the upperwing coverts lacking any obvious contrast.  I am less sure about the color if the primary coverts, however.  The tertials were the same green as the coverts, and I suspect the secondaries were as well, though my recollection of this is not as good.  I did note quite clearly in the field that the exposed primaries were a sky-blue color that contrasted conspicuously with the mostly green wings, but I was unsure if the inner webs of the primaries were similarly colored.  I am confident that the upperside of the tail was green, but I am less sure if it was the same shade as the wings, or possibly a bit darker. The bill was a deep flesh color, and the toes were gray with a pinkish cast when seen in good light.  My photos show the eyes to be quite dark and that they were encircled by a light gray orbital-ring, neither of which I could recall from my field observations.

Previously reported; a lifer for me! Found the massive stick nest atop the utility pole first, then waited over an hour for the bird to arrive. Eventually it flew into the nest at about 7:30, and about twenty minutes later it came almost fully out, sitting on the edge to scratch its head and watch the sunset. Retreated back into the nest at about 8 PM, presumably for the night. Shockingly green on the back and wings, with a grey forehead, cheeks, chest, and stomach. Pale peachy-orange bill. Perhaps about the size of a dove, maybe a little smaller.

In previously reported roost location along the elevated Henry Hudson Parkway between 155th and 159th, clearly visible from the Greenway path. Bright green above, white below, white face, orange/pink bill, long tail, a little smaller than a pigeon, raucous call. I saw two at the roost, which I watched for twenty minutes or so as the two birds there took turns flying out and returning with thick twigs; they called while leaving and while returning. Also heard another calling from under the parkway while I watched the roost; saw 4 flying at once a little south of 155th; saw several individuals in other locations along the Greenway, calling from trees. Calling it 4 since I can't prove any of them weren't part of the largest group I saw, but I suspect I saw 6-8 in all, and there are probably more--I didn't search under the elevated highway for more roosts.

Walking north on 31st Av S, I heard a loud screech in a tree in boulevard on east side of the road. I stopped and looked but couldn’t locate bird, though it had sounded as if it were right above me. Then it flew past, a lime green streak. It perched on a high branch of a tree in a yard a few doors south on 31st. I had my binoculars with me and quickly saw it was a parrot — or, as I learned later, a parakeet. I immediately took it for an escaped pet. Generally green, with a gray forehead (so to speak), lower face, throat, & breast. My partner took a few pictures (attached), and we pointed it out to the family in whose yard the bird was now perched. We watched it for five minutes, then left.

Continuing birds first located by Jesse Pope a few days ago.  I first spotted one bird perched next to its nest on the transformer station.  A few minutes later the other bird flew in and perched next to the first.  Later, they flew behind the transformer station (as seen from Sweetwater Branch road) and found an apple tree with some still hanging fruit.  I observed them eat that fruit, and so it seems they have some source of food beyond the local feeders.  Later, I observed one of the two snap off a twig and then take it to the nest, indicating, as Jesse noted, that they are actively building the nest.  Please see the attached pictures which show the two birds near their nest, one feeding on an apple, and one flying with a twig in its beak.

Locality: Tijuana River Valley--Sunset Ave east of Hollister
Observation Details: Unexpected and from my understanding quite scarce in the TRV. This bird was detected initially by call and made a brief fly-by at a distance of 150 yards or so. After a short period of time the bird dipped below the tree-line and I lost it. This was an unmistakable medium-sized parakeet that was an overall lime green parakeet with darker bluish tips on the upperwing, white throat and crown that gradually faded to a yellowish then eventually green belly, and thick pinkish bill. The bird was giving “parrot like” calls while flying that I immediately recognized as some sort of parrot or parakeet. Based on my knowledge these birds are somewhat readily established further south in Tijuana, and occasionally stray up into the TRV.

Observation Details: I thought it was fun to see that the Monk Parakeet, although recorded in other areas of the Mediterranean, had not been recorded in eBird in Marseille. I had seen them in Spain nesting in large electric towers where they built giant nests filling the spaces between metal bars. I have read in eBird they are the only parrot that build stick nests as well, which surely helps to identify them.  I also learned from reading that they can live in urban areas as Rock Doves / pigeons do.  I have seen urban introduced parakeets in Marseille and Barcelona, the Ring-necked Parakeet (Psittacula krameri) (I have not made a complete list of them in ebird yet!), and noticed the differences between them and the Monk Parakeet. The Monk Parakeets I have observed are bright green backed parakeets around the size of a European Blackbird with a light grey throat, breast and forehead. There is also blue at the end of the wings, but it is not always easy to see. I saw some blue color in a photo I took of a bird in flight. The Ring-necked Parakeet is also bright green all over and  lacks the light grey in the breast and on the forehead and has a quite noticeable bright, deep red bill, contrasting with the green plumage. For me the head proportion of the head of the Monk Parakeet is larger in comparison to it´s body than that of the Ring-necked Parakeet, that appears to have a smaller head in proportion to it's body. The Monk Parakeets I have seen in the park were raucous with their loud calls. They have built four, very large, nests with branches in the sycamore trees in this park. They entered and exited their nests during the observation period. They also foraged on the ground with the pigeons collecting morsels of bread and then flying to branches to eat it. I noticed, and included, a mediocre photo of one Monk Parakeet holding a morsel of bread with its foot and lifting it to eat. This is a behavior I have seen with other parrot species.

I saw eleven adult birds perched on a fence beside Calle Guadalhorce when I was walking towards the reserve entrance. Photographs were taken. Also, while walking round the reserve I saw about 30 adult birds flying over the reserve. They were flying quickly and calling noisily. In fact I heard them long before I saw them. Photographs were taken. Two adults were also seen perched together in a bush on the large island in Laguna Grande.  Groups/Flocks, Flew Overhead, Calling noisily, Perched, Photograph.  43 adults.

I saw many groups of birds of this species flying across the reserve. The group size varied from two to eighteen. Most were flying from Guadalmar to Málaga. They flew very low and were surprisingly difficult to see until they were on top of you. They also squawked loudly as they flew. One grouped perched in an open bush and I managed to get some photographs.  Flying Over, Calling, Perched, Photograph.  75 adults.
